### Introduction:

This exercise is based on the titanic Disaster dataset avaiable at [Kaggle](https://www.kaggle.com/c/titanic).  
To know more about the variables check [here](https://www.kaggle.com/c/titanic/data)

It is recomended also to use **seaborn** library

### Step 1. Import the necessary libraries

# El "ipython magic" que permite ver los plots en notebooks
%matplotlib inline

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
import re
from azureml import Workspace
### Step 2. Import the dataset from titanic.csv
### Step 3. Assign it to a variable titanic

ws = Workspace()
ds = ws.datasets['titanic.csv']
titanic = ds.to_dataframe()
### Step 4. Set PassengerId as the index

# With set index, we can set a column like index
titanic.set_index('PassengerId')
# Checking if everything is ok
titanic.head()

             diag_kind='kde',
             palette="husl",
             markers=["+", "."],
             plot_kws={'alpha': 0.2})

cells.source: ### Step 6. Create a scatterplot with the Fare payed and the Age, differ the plot color by gender

# Creating plot with X=Age and Y=Fare and hue=Sex
lm = sns.lmplot(x = 'Age', y = 'Fare', data = titanic, hue = 'Sex', fit_reg=False)

# We optionally can set a title
lm.set(title = 'Fare vs Age')
### Step 8. Create a histogram with the Fare payed

# Selecting variable, we can plot their histogram
titanic.Fare.hist()
### Step 9: Create a diagonal correlation plot af all variables ([tip](http://seaborn.pydata.org/examples/many_pairwise_correlations.html))

corr = titanic.corr()

# Generate a mask for the upper triangle
mask = np.zeros_like(corr, dtype=np.bool)
mask[np.triu_indices_from(mask)] = True

# Set up the matplotlib figure
f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(11, 9))

# Generate a custom diverging colormap
cmap = sns.diverging_palette(220, 10, as_cmap=True)

# Draw the heatmap with the mask and correct aspect ratio
sns.heatmap(corr, mask=mask, cmap=cmap, vmax=0.3, center=0,
                square=True, linewidths=.5, cbar_kws={"shrink": .5})
